{"title_page": "Roger Knapman", "text_new": "{{short description|Former Leader of the UK Independence Party}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name             = Roger Knapman\n|smallimage       = Roger Knapman.jpg\n|office           = [[List of UK Independence Party leaders|Leader of the UK Independence Party]]\n|deputy = [[Mike Nattrass]]\n|1blankname = [[Party Chair|Chairman]]\n|1namedata = [[David Lott]]<br />[[Petrina Holdsworth]]<br />[[David Campbell Bannerman]]\n|predecessor      = [[Jeffrey Titford]]\n|successor        = [[Nigel Farage]]\n|term_start       = 5 October 2002\n|term_end         = 27 September 2006\n|office1          = [[Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]\n|primeminister1 = [[John Major]]\n|term_start1      = 23 July 1996\n|term_end1        = 1 May 1997\n|predecessor1 = [[Simon Burns]]\n|successor1 = [[Bob Ainsworth]]\n|office3          = [[Member of the European Parliament]] <br />for  [[South West England (European Parliament constituency)|South West England & Gibraltar]]\n|predecessor3     = [[Alexander Macmillan, 2nd Earl of Stockton|The Earl of Stockton]]\n|successor3       = [[William Legge, 10th Earl of Dartmouth|The Earl of Dartmouth]]\n|term_start3      = 10 June 2004\n|term_end3        = 4 June 2009\n|office4          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Stroud (UK Parliament constituency)|Stroud]]\n|predecessor4     = [[Anthony Kershaw|Sir Anthony Kershaw]]\n|successor4       = [[David Drew (politician)|David Drew]]\n|term_start4      = 11 June 1987\n|term_end4        = 1 May 1997\n|birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1944|02|20|df=yes}}\n|birth_place      = [[Crediton]], [[Devon]], [[United Kingdom]]\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|nationality      = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n|spouse           = Carolyn Knapman <ref>{{cite web|author=Culture |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/3641431/A-quiet-life-on-the-fringes-of-power.html |title=A quiet life on the fringes of power |publisher=Telegraph |date=2005-05-03 |accessdate=2014-05-20}}</ref>\n|party            = [[UK Independence Party]]<small> (Since 1997) </small><br />[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] <small> (Before 1997) </small>\n|relations        = \n|children         = 2\n|residence        = United Kingdom\n|alma_mater       = [[Royal Agricultural College]]\n|occupation       = \n|profession       = \n|religion         = \n|signature        = \n|website          = \n|footnotes        = \n}}\n\n'''Roger Maurice Knapman''' (born 20 February 1944 in [[Crediton]], [[Devon]]) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[politician]] who served as a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MP before becoming leader of the [[UK Independence Party]] (UKIP).\n\n==Early life==\nThe son of Harry Arthur Blackmore Knapman, a farmer, and Joan Margot n\u00e9e Densham,<ref>She died before 1991.</ref> Roger Knapman was educated at Allhallows School, Lyme Regis, and the [[Royal Agricultural College]], Cirencester.  Before entering politics, he was a [[Chartered Surveyor]] and partner with West Country, a firm of livestock auctioneers and surveyors, 1963\u201377. He was then a Chartered Surveyor in his own right 1978\u201385.<ref>''Dod's Parliamentary Companion 1991'', 159th Year, 172nd edition, Hurst Green, Sussex, p.502. {{ISBN|0-905702-17-1}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nAs a member of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]], Knapman was elected [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]] for [[Stroud (UK Parliament constituency)|Stroud]] in [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]], and was Vice-Chairman of the Conservative European Affairs Committee.<ref>''Dod's 1991'', p.502.</ref>  Between 1990 and 1992, he served as\n[[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to the armed forces minister, [[Archibald Gavin Hamilton|Archie Hamilton]]. In this capacity he joined the [[Conservative Monday Club]]'s Foreign Affairs Committee Delegation to the Croatian Government in October 1991 to observe their war of independence against [[Serbia]]. He resigned from his government position in order to oppose the [[Maastricht Treaty]].  He successfully defended his seat in the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]].  In 1995 he became a government [[whip (politics)|whip]]. In [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]], however, he lost his seat to the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] candidate, [[David Drew (politician)|David Drew]].\n\n==UKIP==\nShortly afterwards, Knapman left the Conservative party to join UKIP. He stood as their candidate in the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]] for [[North Devon (UK Parliament constituency)|North Devon]], coming fourth yet narrowly retaining his deposit.\n\nFrom 2000, he was UKIP's political advisor, and in 2002 he was elected unopposed as party leader.  In [[2004 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2004]] he was elected a [[Member of the European Parliament]] for the [[South West England (European Parliament constituency)|South West England]] constituency.  As leader of the only British party in the European Parliament to vote against the expansion of the EU in 2004 (and publicly opposing immigration), there was some amusement in May 2006 when it was revealed that he had employed a team of Polish builders to renovate his Grade II listed home in Devon, claiming there were no suitable local workers \u2013 a claim denied by local builders.\n\nHe contested [[Totnes (UK Parliament constituency)|Totnes]] at the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]], coming 4th with 7.7% of the vote.\n\nIn 2006, he announced that he had no intention of seeking re-election as party leader; the [[2006 UK Independence Party leadership election|leadership contest]] was won in September of that year by [[Nigel Farage]] MEP. Knapman was the only leader of UKIP to have succeeded in completing a full four-year term until Farage did so in 2014 after returning to the role in 2010.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Hansard-contribs|mr-roger-knapman|Roger Knapman}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.rogerknapmanmep.co.uk/}}\n*[http://www.europarl.europa.eu/members/public/geoSearch/view.do?country=GB&partNumber=1&zone=South+West&language=EN&id=28505 Profile at European Parliament website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Stroud (UK Parliament constituency)|Stroud]]|years=[[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]]\u2013[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]|before=[[Anthony Kershaw]]|after= [[David Drew (politician)|David Drew]]\n}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box|before=[[Jeffrey Titford]]|title=Leader of the [[United Kingdom Independence Party]]|years=2002\u20132006|after=[[Nigel Farage]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Leaders of the United Kingdom Independence Party}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knapman, Roger Maurice}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Agricultural University]]\n[[Category:British libertarians]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the UK Independence Party]]\n[[Category:Members of the European Parliament for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 2004\u20132009]]\n[[Category:People from Crediton]]\n[[Category:UK Independence Party MEPs]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1987\u20131992]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1992\u20131997]]\n[[Category:UK Independence Party parliamentary candidates]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Former Leader of the UK Independence Party}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name             = Roger Knapman\n|smallimage       = Roger Knapman.jpg\n|office           = [[List of UK Independence Party leaders|Leader of the UK Independence Party]]\n|deputy = [[Mike Nattrass]]\n|1blankname = [[Party Chair|Chairman]]\n|1namedata = [[David Lott]]<br />[[Petrina Holdsworth]]<br />[[David Campbell Bannerman]]\n|predecessor      = [[Jeffrey Titford]]\n|successor        = [[Nigel Farage]]\n|term_start       = 5 October 2002\n|term_end         = 27 September 2006\n|office1          = [[Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]\n|primeminister1 = [[John Major]]\n|term_start1      = 23 July 1996\n|term_end1        = 1 May 1997\n|predecessor1 = [[Simon Burns]]\n|successor1 = [[Bob Ainsworth]]\n|office3          = [[Member of the European Parliament]] <br />for  [[South West England (European Parliament constituency)|South West England & Gibraltar]]\n|predecessor3     = [[Alexander Macmillan, 2nd Earl of Stockton|The Earl of Stockton]]\n|successor3       = [[William Legge, 10th Earl of Dartmouth|The Earl of Dartmouth]]\n|term_start3      = 10 June 2004\n|term_end3        = 4 June 2009\n|office4          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Stroud (UK Parliament constituency)|Stroud]]\n|predecessor4     = [[Anthony Kershaw|Sir Anthony Kershaw]]\n|successor4       = [[David Drew (politician)|David Drew]]\n|term_start4      = 11 June 1987\n|term_end4        = 1 May 1997\n|birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1944|02|20|df=yes}}\n|birth_place      = [[Crediton]], [[Devon]], [[United Kingdom]]\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|nationality      = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n|spouse           = Carolyn Knapman <ref>{{cite web|author=Culture |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/3641431/A-quiet-life-on-the-fringes-of-power.html |title=A quiet life on the fringes of power |publisher=Telegraph |date=2005-05-03 |accessdate=2014-05-20}}</ref>\n|party            = [[UK Independence Party]]<small> (Since 1997) </small><br />[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] <small> (Before 1997) </small>\n|relations        = \n|children         = 2\n|residence        = United Kingdom\n|alma_mater       = [[Royal Agricultural College]]\n|occupation       = \n|profession       = \n|religion         = \n|signature        = \n|website          = \n|footnotes        = \n}}\n\n'''Roger Maurice Knapman''' (born 20 February 1944 in [[Crediton]], [[Devon]]) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[politician]] who served as a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MP before becoming leader of the [[UK Independence Party]] (UKIP).\n\n==Early life==\nThe son of Harry Arthur Blackmore Knapman, a farmer, and Joan Margot n\u00e9e Densham,<ref>She died before 1991.</ref> Roger Knapman was educated at Allhallows School, Lyme Regis, and the [[Royal Agricultural College]], Cirencester.  Before entering politics, he was a [[Chartered Surveyor]] and partner with West Country, a firm of livestock auctioneers and surveyors, 1963-77. He was then a Chartered Surveyor in his own right 1978-85.<ref>''Dod's Parliamentary Companion 1991'', 159th Year, 172nd edition, Hurst Green, Sussex, p.502. {{ISBN|0-905702-17-1}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nAs a member of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]], Knapman was elected [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]] for [[Stroud (UK Parliament constituency)|Stroud]] in [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]], and was Vice-Chairman of the Conservative European Affairs Committee.<ref>''Dod's 1991'', p.502.</ref>  Between 1990 and 1992, he served as\n[[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to the armed forces minister, [[Archibald Gavin Hamilton|Archie Hamilton]]. In this capacity he joined the [[Conservative Monday Club]]'s Foreign Affairs Committee Delegation to the Croatian Government in October 1991 to observe their war of independence against [[Serbia]]. He resigned from his government position in order to oppose the [[Maastricht Treaty]].  He successfully defended his seat in the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]].  In 1995 he became a government [[whip (politics)|whip]]. In [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]], however, he lost his seat to the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] candidate, [[David Drew (politician)|David Drew]].\n\n==UKIP==\nShortly afterwards, Knapman left the Conservative party to join UKIP. He stood as their candidate in the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]] for [[North Devon (UK Parliament constituency)|North Devon]], coming fourth yet narrowly retaining his deposit.\n\nFrom 2000, he was UKIP's political advisor, and in 2002 he was elected unopposed as party leader.  In [[2004 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2004]] he was elected a [[Member of the European Parliament]] for the [[South West England (European Parliament constituency)|South West England]] constituency.  As leader of the only British party in the European Parliament to vote against the expansion of the EU in 2004 (and publicly opposing immigration), there was some amusement in May 2006 when it was revealed that he had employed a team of Polish builders to renovate his Grade II listed home in Devon, claiming there were no suitable local workers \u2013 a claim denied by local builders.\n\nHe contested [[Totnes (UK Parliament constituency)|Totnes]] at the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]], coming 4th with 7.7% of the vote.\n\nIn 2006, he announced that he had no intention of seeking re-election as party leader; the [[2006 UK Independence Party leadership election|leadership contest]] was won in September of that year by [[Nigel Farage]] MEP. Knapman was the only leader of UKIP to have succeeded in completing a full four-year term until Farage did so in 2014 after returning to the role in 2010.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Hansard-contribs|mr-roger-knapman|Roger Knapman}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.rogerknapmanmep.co.uk/}}\n*[http://www.europarl.europa.eu/members/public/geoSearch/view.do?country=GB&partNumber=1&zone=South+West&language=EN&id=28505 Profile at European Parliament website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Stroud (UK Parliament constituency)|Stroud]]|years=[[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]]\u2013[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]|before=[[Anthony Kershaw]]|after= [[David Drew (politician)|David Drew]]\n}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box|before=[[Jeffrey Titford]]|title=Leader of the [[United Kingdom Independence Party]]|years=2002\u20132006|after=[[Nigel Farage]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Leaders of the United Kingdom Independence Party}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knapman, Roger Maurice}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Agricultural University]]\n[[Category:British libertarians]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the UK Independence Party]]\n[[Category:Members of the European Parliament for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the United Kingdom 2004\u20132009]]\n[[Category:People from Crediton]]\n[[Category:UK Independence Party MEPs]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1987\u20131992]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1992\u20131997]]\n[[Category:UK Independence Party parliamentary candidates]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1963-77 \u2192 1963\u201377 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roger_Knapman"}
{"title_page": "Ottavio Bottecchia", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name        = Ottavio Bottecchia\n| image       = Ottavio Bottecchia 1923.jpg\n| caption     = Bottecchia in 1923\n| full_name   = Ottavio Bottecchia\n| nickname    = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|df=yes|1894|08|01}}\n| birth_place = [[Colle Umberto|San Martino di Colle Umberto]], [[Italy]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|df=yes|1927|06|15|1894|08|01}}\n| death_place = [[Gemona]], Italy\n| height      = \n| weight      = \n| discipline  = Road\n| role        = Rider\n| ridertype   = \n| proyears1   = 1922\u201326\n| proteam1    = Automoto-Hutchinson\n| majorwins   = '''[[Grand Tour (cycling)|Grand Tours]]'''\n:'''[[Tour de France]]'''\n:[[General classification in the Tour de France|General classification]] ([[1924 Tour de France|1924]], [[1925 Tour de France|1925]])\n::9 individual stages ([[1923 Tour de France|1923]], [[1924 Tour de France|1924]], [[1925 Tour de France|1925]])\n}}\n\n'''Ottavio Bottecchia''' ({{IPA-it|ot\u02c8tavjo bot\u02c8tekkja|pron}}; 1 August 1894 \u2013 15 June 1927<ref name=\"SiteDuCyc\">{{Cycling Archives|2510}}</ref>) was an [[Italy|Italian]] cyclist and the first Italian winner of the [[Tour de France]].\n\nHe was found dead by the roadside; the reason remains a mystery.\n\n== Early life ==\nBottecchia was born as the eighth child of a poor family of nine children. He went to school for just a year,<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\">{{cite web|url=https://www.humanite.fr/node/287999|title=L'Humanite, 7 July 2003, Sports, Article on Ottavio Bottecchia, Le maillot noir|publisher=}}</ref> first working as a shoemaker, then as a bricklayer.<ref name=\"SiteDuCyc\" /><ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" /><ref name=\"Foot\">{{cite book|last1=Foot|first1=John|title=Pedalare! Pedalare!|date=2011|publisher=Bloomsbury|location=New York}}</ref> His father left to find work in Germany.<ref name=\"Foot\" /> Bottecchia later married and had three children.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nDespite being a convinced socialist with anti-Fascist convictions, Bottecchia joined the [[Bersaglieri]] corps of the Italian army during the [[World War I|first world war]].<ref name=\"Foot\" /> For four years he ferried messages and supplies on the [[Austrians|Austrian]] front with a special folding bicycle. During the conflict he contracted malaria and also had to evade capture several times.<ref>Foot says Bottecchia escaped capture twice, but ''La Gazzetta'' refers to three escapes.</ref> Bottecchia endured a gas attack on 3 November 1917 after the battle of [[Caporetto]] while providing covering fire for retreating forces. Near [[Sequals]] he was captured, but escaped while being marched into captivity at night. After returning to Italian lines, he twice conducted reconnaissance sorties into Austrian-held areas, which by now included his home region of [[Colle Umberto]].<ref name=Gazzetta>{{cite news|last1=Gregori|first1=Claudio|title=Bottecchia, il primo italiano a vincere il Tour, fu eroe della ritirata di Caporetto [Bottecchia, the first Italian to win the Tour, was a hero of the retreat from Caporetto]|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=it&u=http://www.gazzetta.it/Ciclismo/28-07-2014/bottecchia-primo-italiano-vincere-tour-fu-eroe-ritirata-caporetto-801377026351.shtml&prev=search|accessdate=6 December 2014|work=La Gazetta dello Sport|date=July 29, 2014}}</ref> Bottecchia was later awarded a bronze medal<ref>According to Foot the medal awarded to Bottecchia was a silver medal. ''La Gazetta'' indicates that the silver medal was awarded to his brother.</ref> for valor.<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" /><ref name=\"Foot\" />\n\nAfter the end of hostilities Bottecchia moved to France in 1919 to work as a builder, which later led to insinuations that he was not Italian \u2013 slurs that were compounded by his strong regional dialect. Bottecchia's family continued to struggle with poverty, and his youngest daughter died in 1921 at the age of seven.<ref name=\"Foot\" />\n\nBottecchia returned to Italy where he took up competitive cycling.<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" /><ref name=\"Foot\" /> He won the Giro del Piave, the Coppa della Vittoria, and the Duca D'Aosta in 1920 and the Coppe Gallo an Osimo, the Circuito del Piave and the Giro del Friuli in 1921.<ref name=\"BottBikes\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20100212202946/http://www.bottecchia.com.au/aboutbottecchia-ottavio.html Bottecchia Bikes, About Ottavio Bottecchia]</ref>\n\n== Professional career ==\nBottecchia became a professional cyclist in 1920.<ref>The manufacturer of Bottecchia bicycles offers two dates for the start of the cyclist's professional career. Bottecchia.com says that he was in his third year as a professional when he won the Giro in 1923, while the company's Australian site refers to 1922.</ref> He was given a racing bicycle by Teodoro Carnielli,<ref>Carnielli owned a small bicycle manufacturing company which today still produces Bottecchia bicycles.</ref> president of a cycling association, the Associazione Sportiva di Vittorio Veneto. Carnielli encouraged Bottecchia to join the [[Pordenone]] sport union.<ref name=History>{{cite web|title=History \u2013 Ottavio Bottechia|url=http://www.bottecchia.com/en/company/history/index.html|website=Bottecchia.com|accessdate=6 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214110840/http://www.bottecchia.com/en/company/history/index.html|archive-date=14 December 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1923 Bottecchia placed fifth in the 11th [[Giro d'Italia]], the highest finish by an 'isolate' (rider without a team). His position attracted the leading French rider, [[Henri P\u00e9lissier]], who asked Bottecchia to join his professional team, Automoto-Hutchinson.<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" /><ref name=\"BottBikes\" /><ref>An alternative version of Bottecchia's recruitment has it that Automoto's Aldo Borella approached him after the Giro win.</ref> P\u00e9lissier had just left the J. B. Louvet team after an internal row and had taken another rider, [[Honor\u00e9 Barth\u00e9lemy]], with him. Automoto was a French motorcycle company that also sold its products in Italy. [[Automoto]] saw the chance not only of winning the Tour de France but of having a further Italian rider to stimulate foreign sales. Henri P\u00e9lissier said he had seen Bottecchia ride the [[Giro di Lombardia]] and [[Milan\u2013San Remo]] and the team signed him.<ref name=\"Chany 190\" />\n\nThe new recruit reported for duties with his new team in France, said the writer [[Pierre Chany]], with a skin tanned like an old leather saddle and creases to his face deep enough to be scars. His clothing was ragged and his shoes so old that they no longer had any shape.<ref name=\"Chany 190\">Chany, Pierre (1988), La Fabuleuse Histoire du Tour de France, Nathan, France, pp189-190</ref> His ears stuck out so far that the Tour organiser, [[Henri Desgrange]] referred to him as \"butterfly\".<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" />\n{{cquote|The only words of French he could manage were: \"No bananas, lots of coffee, thank you.\"<ref name=\"Chany 195\">Chany, Pierre (1988), La Fabuleuse Histoire du Tour de France, Nathan, France, pp194-195</ref>}}\n\nIt was as a professional that Bottecchia learned to read, taught by his friend and training partner, Alfonso Piccin. Together they read the Italian sports daily, [[Gazzetta dello Sport]], and clandestine anti-[[fascist]] pamphlets protesting at the rule of [[Benito Mussolini]].<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" />\n\nBottecchia's success for his new team included winning a stage in the 1923 [[Tour de France]], where he also placed second overall. He led the Tour from [[Cherbourg]] after the second stage and wore the [[yellow jersey]] of leader as far as [[Nice]]. There he passed it on to P\u00e9lissier, who won with the prediction: \"Bottecchia will succeed me next year.\"<ref name=\"Chany 195\" /> Such was the reaction in Italy that the ''Gazetta dello Sport'' asked a [[Italian lira|lire]] from each of its readers to reward him. Mussolini was first to subscribe.<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" />\n\nIn 1924 Bottecchia won the first stage of the Tour and kept his lead to the end, the first Italian to win.<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" /> He wore his yellow jersey all the way to [[Milan]] in the train<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" /> \u2013 travelling third class to save money. {{cquote|By then his French had improved to: \"Not tired, French and Belgians good friends, cycling good job.\"<ref name=\"Chany 195\" />}}\n\nBottecchia won the Tour again in 1925 with the help of [[Lucien Buysse]], who served as the first [[cycling domestique|domestique]] in Tour history. Accused in 1924 of winning without trying, Bottecchia won the first, sixth, seventh and final stage.\nHe was never the same after that and dropped out, \"weeping like a child\",<ref>L'\u00c9quipe 24 June 2003</ref> during a thunderstorm in 1926. Buysse emerged the winner. The writer [[Bernard Chambaz]] said:\n\n<blockquote>The unpleasant hand of destiny fell on his shoulders. It was as though the misery of his origins had caught up with him. Dark thoughts and a presentiment of the future haunted him.  He abandoned the Tour of 1926 on a stage which those who were there described as apocalytpic because of the cold and the violence of the wind. He went home, unhappy. He no longer had the heart to train. He feared that he'd been 'cut down by a bad illness'. He coughed and he ached in his back and his bronchial tubes. The following winter, he lost his younger brother, knocked down by a car.<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" /></blockquote>\n\n== Death ==\n[[File:Trasaghis Monumento Bottecchia 01112007 02.jpg|thumb|Monument to Bottecchia at [[Trasaghis]] by the [[Tagliamento]] river]]\nOn May 23, 1927, Ottavio's brother, Giovanni, was riding his bike near [[Conegliano]] when a car hit him and killed him.<ref name=\"Bro Death\">{{cite news|url=http://www.archiviolastampa.it/component/option,com_lastampa/task,search/mod,libera/action,viewer/Itemid,3/page,6/articleid,1160_01_1927_0122_0004_24378927/anews,true/|title=Il fratello di Bottecchia|language=Italian|date=May 24, 1927|page=4|newspaper=La Stampa|author=|publisher=Editrice La Stampa|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans-title=The brother of Bottecchia}}</ref> Ottavio returned to Italy from France because of the death.<ref name=\"LS Giro\">{{cite news|url=http://www.archiviolastampa.it/component/option,com_lastampa/task,search/mod,libera/action,viewer/Itemid,3/page,4/articleid,1160_01_1927_0131_0004_24876744/|title=La Prima Vittoria di Brunero|language=Italian|date=June 3, 1927|page=4|newspaper=La Stampa|author=Giuseppe Tonelli|publisher=Editrice La Stampa|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans-title=The First Victory of Brunero}}</ref> While back, he led the peloton at the [[1927 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]] on June 2.<ref name=\"LS Giro\" />\n\nOn 3 June 1927, a farmer outside the village of Peonis, near Bottecchia's home, found him on the roadside.  His skull was cracked, one collarbone and other bones broken.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/features.php?id=features/2007/woodland_murders07|title=www.cyclingnews.com \u2013 the world centre of cycling|website=autobus.cyclingnews.com}}</ref> His bike lay some distance away on the verge and wasn't damaged. There were no skid marks to suggest a car had forced him off the road and no marks to the pedals or handlebar tape to suggest he'd lost control.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nBottecchia was carried to an inn and laid on a table.<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" /> A priest gave him the [[last rites]]. From there he was taken by cart to hospital in Gemona. He died there on June 14, twelve days later,<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" /> without regaining consciousness.<ref>Het Raadsel van Peonis, Wielerrevue, Netherlands, undated cutting</ref><ref name=\"LS Death\">{{cite news|url=http://www.archiviolastampa.it/component/option,com_lastampa/task,search/mod,libera/action,viewer/Itemid,3/page,3/articleid,1160_01_1927_0142_0003_24379379/anews,true/|title=La morte di Bottecchia|language=Italian|date=June 15, 1927|page=3|newspaper=La Stampa|publisher=Editrice La Stampa|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans-title=The Death of Bottecchai}}</ref>\n\nThe day of his death Bottecchia had risen at dawn and asked for a hot bath to be ready for him for when he would return in three hours. He rode to his friend Alfonso Piccini's house to go training together as on other days. Piccini decided not to go and Bottecchia went to see another friend, Riccardo Zille. He had other things to do, however, so Bottecchia set out alone.<ref>Spitaleri, Enrico, Delitto Bottecchia, Antonion Pellicani, Italy</ref>\n\nTheories abound about the circumstances of his death. Bernard Chambaz of ''[[L'Humanit\u00e9]]'' said:\n<blockquote>Accident or assassination? The accident theory, favoured by justice, on the accounts of witnesses and a medical examination which also referred to several fractures, was based on an assumption of an illness, sunstroke and a fall. In fact, the inquiry was quickly closed. The theory suited everybody: the Mussolini r\u00e9gime, the presumed killer and even \u2013 it's sad to say \u2013 the family, now sure of a large insurance payout.<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" /></blockquote>\n\nDon Dant\u0117 Nigris, the priest who gave him the last rites, is said to have attributed the death to Fascists unhappy about Bottecchia's more liberal leanings.<ref name=Startt>{{cite book|last1=Startt|first1=James|title=Tour de France/Tour de Force \u2013 a Visual History of the World's Greatest Bicycle Race|date=2000|publisher=Chronicle Books|location=San Francisco|page=41}}</ref> But an Italian dying from stab wounds on a New York waterfront claimed he had been employed as a hit man.<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" /><ref name=Startt /> He named a supposed godfather, although nobody of the name was ever found.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nMuch later, the farmer who had found him said on his deathbed:<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" /> \"I saw a man eating my grapes. He'd pushed through the vines and damaged them. I threw a rock to scare him, but it hit him. I ran to him and realised who it was. I panicked and dragged him to the roadside and left him. God forgive me!\"\n\n''Note. However at the beginning of June grapes are unripe and inedible.''\n\n{{Quote box\n| quote = \"Bottecchia was a revelation. His name will stay inseparable from the Tour de France.\"\n| source = ''Miroir des Sports'', 21 June 1927,<ref>Le Miroir des Sports, France, 21 June 1927</ref>\n| width  = 550px\n | align  =center\n}}\n\n== Bottecchia bicycles ==\nIn 1926, [[Bottecchia]] began working with frame-maker Teodoro Carnielli to manufacture racing bikes, taking advantage of his Tour de France knowledge.<ref name=\"BottBikes\" /> The business expanded under the Carnielli family after Bottecchia's death. In 2006 more than 50,000 Bottechia bikes were sold in Europe.<ref name=\"BottBikes\" />\n\n== Literary relevance ==\nBottecchia is mentioned at the end of [[Ernest Hemingway]]'s ''[[The Sun Also Rises]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gilhaney.wordpress.com/2009/11/16/a-splendid-thing/|title=A splendid thing|date=16 November 2009}}</ref>\n\n== Career achievements ==\n{{unref|section|date=July 2019}}\n=== Major results ===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{Col-break}}\n;1923\n:[[1923 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Second place overall classification\n::Winner stage 2\n::Wearing [[yellow jersey]] for 6 non-consecutive days\n{{col-break}}\n;1924\n:[[1924 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::[[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] '''Winner overall classification'''\n::Winner stages 1, 6, 7 and 15\n::Wearing yellow jersey for 15 days (the entire race).\n{{col-break}}\n;1925\n:Giro della provincia Milano\n:[[1925 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::[[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] '''Winner overall classification'''\n::Winner stages 1, 6, 7 and 18\n::Wearing yellow jersey for 13 non-consecutive days.\n{{col-end}}\n\n=== Grand Tour results timeline ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|\n! scope=\"col\" | 1923\n! scope=\"col\" | 1924\n! scope=\"col\" | 1925\n! scope=\"col\" | 1926\n|-\n![[Giro d'Italia]]\n|align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EEE8AA;\"| [[1923 Giro d'Italia|5]]\n|align=\"center\" | DNE\n|align=\"center\" | DNE\n|align=\"center\" | DNE\n|-\n|align=\"right\" |Stages won\n|align=\"center\"| 0\n|align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|-\n![[Tour de France]]\n|align=\"center\" style=\"background:#D8BFD8;\"| [[1923 Tour de France|2]]\n|align=\"center\" style=\"background:#00ff00;\"| [[1924 Tour de France|1]]\n|align=\"center\" style=\"background:#00ff00;\"| [[1925 Tour de France|1]]\n|align=\"center\" style=\"background:#AAAAAA;\"| [[1926 Tour de France|DNF-10]]\n|-\n|align=\"right\" |Stages won\n|align=\"center\"| 1\n|align=\"center\"| 4\n|align=\"center\"| 4\n|align=\"center\"| 0\n|-\n![[Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]]\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\" style=\"color:#888888;\"| N/A\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\" style=\"color:#888888;\"| N/A\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\" style=\"color:#888888;\"| N/A\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\" style=\"color:#888888;\"| N/A\n|-\n|align=\"right\" |Stages won\n|}\n{{grandtourlegend}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Legends of Italian sport - Walk of Fame]]\n\n== References ==\n {{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |first=Claudio |last=Gregori |title=Il Corno di Orlando. Vita, Morte e Misteri di Ottavio Bottecchia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NYFZAQAACAAJ |trans-title=The Horn of Roland. Life, Death and Mysteries of Ottavio Bottecchia |language=Italian |location=Rome, Italy |publisher=66th and 2nd |year=2017 |isbn=978-88-98970-94-0}}\n* {{cite book |first=Paolo |last=Facchinetti |title=Bottecchia. Il Forzato della Strada |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j0GUMEppX3MC |language=Italian |location= |publisher=Ediciclo Editore |year=2005 |isbn=978-88-88829-23-4}}\n* {{cite book |first=Giuliana |last=Fantuz |title=Ottavio Bottecchia\u2014Botesci\u00e0: Bicicletta e Coraggio |language=Italian |publisher=Libreria dello Sport |year=2004 |isbn=978-88-86753-78-4}}\n* {{cite book |first=Elio |last=Bartolini |title=Ottavio Bottecchia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j0GUMEppX3MC |language=Italian |location=Pordenone, Italy |publisher=Edizioni Studio Tesi |year=1992 |isbn=978-88-76923-60-9}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Cycling Archives|2510}}\n*[http://histo.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/coureur/2093.html Official Tour de France results for Ottavio Bottecchia]\n\n{{Tour de France general classification winners}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bottecchia, Ottavio}}\n[[Category:1894 births]]\n[[Category:1927 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Treviso]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Tour de France winners]]\n[[Category:Murdered sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Unsolved murders in Italy]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Veneto]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name        = Ottavio Bottecchia\n| image       = Ottavio Bottecchia 1923.jpg\n| caption     = Bottecchia in 1923\n| full_name   = Ottavio Bottecchia\n| nickname    = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|df=yes|1894|08|01}}\n| birth_place = [[Colle Umberto|San Martino di Colle Umberto]], [[Italy]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|df=yes|1927|06|15|1894|08|01}}\n| death_place = [[Gemona]], Italy\n| height      = \n| weight      = \n| discipline  = Road\n| role        = Rider\n| ridertype   = \n| proyears1   = 1922\u201326\n| proteam1    = Automoto-Hutchinson\n| majorwins   = '''[[Grand Tour (cycling)|Grand Tours]]'''\n:'''[[Tour de France]]'''\n:[[General classification in the Tour de France|General classification]] ([[1924 Tour de France|1924]], [[1925 Tour de France|1925]])\n::9 individual stages ([[1923 Tour de France|1923]], [[1924 Tour de France|1924]], [[1925 Tour de France|1925]])\n}}\n\n'''Ottavio Bottecchia''' ({{IPA-it|ot\u02c8tavjo bot\u02c8tekkja|pron}}; 1 August 1894 \u2013 15 June 1927<ref name=\"SiteDuCyc\">{{Cycling Archives|2510}}</ref>) was an [[Italy|Italian]] cyclist and the first Italian winner of the [[Tour de France]].\n\nHe was found dead by the roadside; the reason remains a mystery.\n\n== Early life ==\nBottecchia was born as the eighth child of a poor family of nine children. He went to school for just a year,<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\">{{cite web|url=https://www.humanite.fr/node/287999|title=L'Humanite, 7 July 2003, Sports, Article on Ottavio Bottecchia, Le maillot noir|publisher=}}</ref> first working as a shoemaker, then as a bricklayer.<ref name=\"SiteDuCyc\" /><ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" /><ref name=\"Foot\">{{cite book|last1=Foot|first1=John|title=Pedalare! Pedalare!|date=2011|publisher=Bloomsbury|location=New York}}</ref> His father left to find work in Germany.<ref name=\"Foot\" /> Bottecchia later married and had three children.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nDespite being a convinced socialist with anti-Fascist convictions, Bottecchia joined the [[Bersaglieri]] corps of the Italian army during the [[World War I|first world war]].<ref name=\"Foot\" /> For four years he ferried messages and supplies on the [[Austrians|Austrian]] front with a special folding bicycle. During the conflict he contracted malaria and also had to evade capture several times.<ref>Foot says Bottecchia escaped capture twice, but ''La Gazzetta'' refers to three escapes.</ref> Bottecchia endured a gas attack on 3 November 1917 after the battle of [[Caporetto]] while providing covering fire for retreating forces. Near [[Sequals]] he was captured, but escaped while being marched into captivity at night. After returning to Italian lines, he twice conducted reconnaissance sorties into Austrian-held areas, which by now included his home region of [[Colle Umberto]].<ref name=Gazzetta>{{cite news|last1=Gregori|first1=Claudio|title=Bottecchia, il primo italiano a vincere il Tour, fu eroe della ritirata di Caporetto [Bottecchia, the first Italian to win the Tour, was a hero of the retreat from Caporetto]|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=it&u=http://www.gazzetta.it/Ciclismo/28-07-2014/bottecchia-primo-italiano-vincere-tour-fu-eroe-ritirata-caporetto-801377026351.shtml&prev=search|accessdate=6 December 2014|work=La Gazetta dello Sport|date=July 29, 2014}}</ref> Bottecchia was later awarded a bronze medal<ref>According to Foot the medal awarded to Bottecchia was a silver medal. ''La Gazetta'' indicates that the silver medal was awarded to his brother.</ref> for valor.<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" /><ref name=\"Foot\" />\n\nAfter the end of hostilities Bottecchia moved to France in 1919 to work as a builder, which later led to insinuations that he was not Italian \u2013 slurs that were compounded by his strong regional dialect. Bottecchia's family continued to struggle with poverty, and his youngest daughter died in 1921 at the age of seven.<ref name=\"Foot\" />\n\nBottecchia returned to Italy where he took up competitive cycling.<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" /><ref name=\"Foot\" /> He won the Giro del Piave, the Coppa della Vittoria, and the Duca D'Aosta in 1920 and the Coppe Gallo an Osimo, the Circuito del Piave and the Giro del Friuli in 1921.<ref name=\"BottBikes\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20100212202946/http://www.bottecchia.com.au/aboutbottecchia-ottavio.html Bottecchia Bikes, About Ottavio Bottecchia]</ref>\n\n== Professional career ==\nBottecchia became a professional cyclist in 1920.<ref>The manufacturer of Bottecchia bicycles offers two dates for the start of the cyclist's professional career. Bottecchia.com says that he was in his third year as a professional when he won the Giro in 1923, while the company's Australian site refers to 1922.</ref> He was given a racing bicycle by Teodoro Carnielli,<ref>Carnielli owned a small bicycle manufacturing company which today still produces Bottecchia bicycles.</ref> president of a cycling association, the Associazione Sportiva di Vittorio Veneto. Carnielli encouraged Bottecchia to join the [[Pordenone]] sport union.<ref name=History>{{cite web|title=History \u2013 Ottavio Bottechia|url=http://www.bottecchia.com/en/company/history/index.html|website=Bottecchia.com|accessdate=6 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214110840/http://www.bottecchia.com/en/company/history/index.html|archive-date=14 December 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1923 Bottecchia placed fifth in the 11th [[Giro d'Italia]], the highest finish by an 'isolate' (rider without a team). His position attracted the leading French rider, [[Henri P\u00e9lissier]], who asked Bottecchia to join his professional team, Automoto-Hutchinson.<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" /><ref name=\"BottBikes\" /><ref>An alternative version of Bottecchia's recruitment has it that Automoto's Aldo Borella approached him after the Giro win.</ref> P\u00e9lissier had just left the J. B. Louvet team after an internal row and had taken another rider, [[Honor\u00e9 Barth\u00e9lemy]], with him. Automoto was a French motorcycle company that also sold its products in Italy. [[Automoto]] saw the chance not only of winning the Tour de France but of having a further Italian rider to stimulate foreign sales. Henri P\u00e9lissier said he had seen Bottecchia ride the [[Giro di Lombardia]] and [[Milan\u2013San Remo]] and the team signed him.<ref name=\"Chany 190\" />\n\nThe new recruit reported for duties with his new team in France, said the writer [[Pierre Chany]], with a skin tanned like an old leather saddle and creases to his face deep enough to be scars. His clothing was ragged and his shoes so old that they no longer had any shape.<ref name=\"Chany 190\">Chany, Pierre (1988), La Fabuleuse Histoire du Tour de France, Nathan, France, pp189-190</ref> His ears stuck out so far that the Tour organiser, [[Henri Desgrange]] referred to him as \"butterfly\".<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" />\n{{cquote|The only words of French he could manage were: \"No bananas, lots of coffee, thank you.\"<ref name=\"Chany 195\">Chany, Pierre (1988), La Fabuleuse Histoire du Tour de France, Nathan, France, pp194-195</ref>}}\n\nIt was as a professional that Bottecchia learned to read, taught by his friend and training partner, Alfonso Piccin. Together they read the Italian sports daily, [[Gazzetta dello Sport]], and clandestine anti-[[fascist]] pamphlets protesting at the rule of [[Benito Mussolini]].<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" />\n\nBottecchia's success for his new team included winning a stage in the 1923 [[Tour de France]], where he also placed second overall. He led the Tour from [[Cherbourg]] after the second stage and wore the [[yellow jersey]] of leader as far as [[Nice]]. There he passed it on to P\u00e9lissier, who won with the prediction: \"Bottecchia will succeed me next year.\"<ref name=\"Chany 195\" /> Such was the reaction in Italy that the ''Gazetta dello Sport'' asked a [[Italian lira|lire]] from each of its readers to reward him. Mussolini was first to subscribe.<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" />\n\nIn 1924 Bottecchia won the first stage of the Tour and kept his lead to the end, the first Italian to win.<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" /> He wore his yellow jersey all the way to [[Milan]] in the train<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" /> \u2013 travelling third class to save money. {{cquote|By then his French had improved to: \"Not tired, French and Belgians good friends, cycling good job.\"<ref name=\"Chany 195\" />}}\n\nBottecchia won the Tour again in 1925 with the help of [[Lucien Buysse]], who served as the first [[cycling domestique|domestique]] in Tour history. Accused in 1924 of winning without trying, Bottecchia won the first, sixth, seventh and final stage.\nHe was never the same after that and dropped out, \"weeping like a child\",<ref>L'\u00c9quipe 24 June 2003</ref> during a thunderstorm in 1926. Buysse emerged the winner. The writer [[Bernard Chambaz]] said:\n\n<blockquote>The unpleasant hand of destiny fell on his shoulders. It was as though the misery of his origins had caught up with him. Dark thoughts and a presentiment of the future haunted him.  He abandoned the Tour of 1926 on a stage which those who were there described as apocalytpic because of the cold and the violence of the wind. He went home, unhappy. He no longer had the heart to train. He feared that he'd been 'cut down by a bad illness'. He coughed and he ached in his back and his bronchial tubes. The following winter, he lost his younger brother, knocked down by a car.<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" /></blockquote>\n\n== Death ==\n[[File:Trasaghis Monumento Bottecchia 01112007 02.jpg|thumb|Monument to Bottecchia at [[Trasaghis]] by the [[Tagliamento]] river]]\nOn May 23, 1927, Ottavio's brother, Giovanni, was riding his bike near [[Conegliano]] when a car hit him and killed him.<ref name=\"Bro Death\">{{cite news|url=http://www.archiviolastampa.it/component/option,com_lastampa/task,search/mod,libera/action,viewer/Itemid,3/page,6/articleid,1160_01_1927_0122_0004_24378927/anews,true/|title=Il fratello di Bottecchia|language=Italian|date=May 24, 1927|page=4|newspaper=La Stampa|author=|publisher=Editrice La Stampa|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans-title=The brother of Bottecchia}}</ref> Ottavio returned to Italy from France because of the death.<ref name=\"LS Giro\">{{cite news|url=http://www.archiviolastampa.it/component/option,com_lastampa/task,search/mod,libera/action,viewer/Itemid,3/page,4/articleid,1160_01_1927_0131_0004_24876744/|title=La Prima Vittoria di Brunero|language=Italian|date=June 3, 1927|page=4|newspaper=La Stampa|author=Giuseppe Tonelli|publisher=Editrice La Stampa|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans-title=The First Victory of Brunero}}</ref> While back, he led the peloton at the [[1927 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]] on June 2.<ref name=\"LS Giro\" />\n\nOn 3 June 1927, a farmer outside the village of Peonis, near Bottecchia's home, found him on the roadside.  His skull was cracked, one collarbone and other bones broken.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/features.php?id=features/2007/woodland_murders07|title=www.cyclingnews.com \u2013 the world centre of cycling|website=autobus.cyclingnews.com}}</ref> His bike lay some distance away on the verge and wasn't damaged. There were no skid marks to suggest a car had forced him off the road and no marks to the pedals or handlebar tape to suggest he'd lost control.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nBottecchia was carried to an inn and laid on a table.<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" /> A priest gave him the [[last rites]]. From there he was taken by cart to hospital in Gemona. He died there on June 14, twelve days later,<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" /> without regaining consciousness.<ref>Het Raadsel van Peonis, Wielerrevue, Netherlands, undated cutting</ref><ref name=\"LS Death\">{{cite news|url=http://www.archiviolastampa.it/component/option,com_lastampa/task,search/mod,libera/action,viewer/Itemid,3/page,3/articleid,1160_01_1927_0142_0003_24379379/anews,true/|title=La morte di Bottecchia|language=Italian|date=June 15, 1927|page=3|newspaper=La Stampa|publisher=Editrice La Stampa|accessdate=27 May 2012|format=PDF|trans-title=The Death of Bottecchai}}</ref>\n\nThe day of his death Bottecchia had risen at dawn and asked for a hot bath to be ready for him for when he would return in three hours. He rode to his friend Alfonso Piccini's house to go training together as on other days. Piccini decided not to go and Bottecchia went to see another friend, Riccardo Zille. He had other things to do, however, so Bottecchia set out alone.<ref>Spitaleri, Enrico, Delitto Bottecchia, Antonion Pellicani, Italy</ref>\n\nTheories abound about the circumstances of his death. Bernard Chambaz of ''[[L'Humanit\u00e9]]'' said:\n<blockquote>Accident or assassination? The accident theory, favoured by justice, on the accounts of witnesses and a medical examination which also referred to several fractures, was based on an assumption of an illness, sunstroke and a fall. In fact, the inquiry was quickly closed. The theory suited everybody: the Mussolini r\u00e9gime, the presumed killer and even \u2013 it's sad to say \u2013 the family, now sure of a large insurance payout.<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" /></blockquote>\n\nDon Dant\u0117 Nigris, the priest who gave him the last rites, is said to have attributed the death to Fascists unhappy about Bottecchia's more liberal leanings.<ref name=Startt>{{cite book|last1=Startt|first1=James|title=Tour de France/Tour de Force \u2013 a Visual History of the World's Greatest Bicycle Race|date=2000|publisher=Chronicle Books|location=San Francisco|page=41}}</ref> But an Italian dying from stab wounds on a New York waterfront claimed he had been employed as a hit man.<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" /><ref name=Startt /> He named a supposed godfather, although nobody of the name was ever found.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nMuch later, the farmer who had found him said on his deathbed:<ref name=\"L'Humanite July 7th 2003\" /> \"I saw a man eating my grapes. He'd pushed through the vines and damaged them. I threw a rock to scare him, but it hit him. I ran to him and realised who it was. I panicked and dragged him to the roadside and left him. God forgive me!\"\n\n''Note. However at the beginning of June grapes are unripe and inedible.''\n\n{{Quote box\n| quote = \"Bottecchia was a revelation. His name will stay inseparable from the Tour de France.\"\n| source = ''Miroir des Sports'', 21 June 1927,<ref>Le Miroir des Sports, France, 21 June 1927</ref>\n| width  = 550px\n | align  =center\n}}\n\n== Bottecchia bicycles ==\nIn 1926, [[Bottecchia]] began working with frame-maker Teodoro Carnielli to manufacture racing bikes, taking advantage of his Tour de France knowledge.<ref name=\"BottBikes\" /> The business expanded under the Carnielli family after Bottecchia's death. In 2006 more than 50,000 Bottechia bikes were sold in Europe.<ref name=\"BottBikes\" />\n\n== Literary relevance ==\nBottecchia is mentioned at the end of [[Ernest Hemingway]]'s ''[[The Sun Also Rises]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gilhaney.wordpress.com/2009/11/16/a-splendid-thing/|title=A splendid thing|date=16 November 2009}}</ref>\n\n== Career achievements ==\n{{unref|section|date=July 2019}}\n=== Major results ===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{Col-break}}\n;1923\n:[[1923 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Second place overall classification\n::Winner stage 2\n::Wearing [[yellow jersey]] for 6 non-consecutive days\n{{col-break}}\n;1924\n:[[1924 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::[[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] '''Winner overall classification'''\n::Winner stages 1, 6, 7 and 15\n::Wearing yellow jersey for 15 days (the entire race).\n{{col-break}}\n;1925\n:Giro della provincia Milano\n:[[1925 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::[[File:Jersey yellow.svg|20px]] '''Winner overall classification'''\n::Winner stages 1, 6, 7 and 18\n::Wearing yellow jersey for 13 non-consecutive days.\n{{col-end}}\n\n=== Grand Tour results timeline ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|\n! scope=\"col\" | 1923\n! scope=\"col\" | 1924\n! scope=\"col\" | 1925\n! scope=\"col\" | 1926\n|-\n![[Giro d'Italia]]\n|align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EEE8AA;\"| [[1923 Giro d'Italia|5]]\n|align=\"center\" | DNE\n|align=\"center\" | DNE\n|align=\"center\" | DNE\n|-\n|align=\"right\" |Stages won\n|align=\"center\"| 0\n|align=\"center\